# Working with a Jupyter notebook
## Managing cells
Jupyter has two modes. When the cell marker is blue, you can select cells with the keyboard arrows and handle them by creating new cells, moving, copying or deleting them. When you press Enter while selecting a cell, you jump into editing mode and can change the content of a cell, e.g. by writing code.

The types of actions you can perform are listed under Help > Keyboard shortcuts 

- New cells are inserted with a (above) or b (below).
- Cells are deleted by pressing d two times.
- To run a cell and select the next cell: Shift + Enter


## Cell types
A Jupyter notebook usually consists of text describing the context of the problem and describing the code as well as the actual code. Text is written in markup cells, which allow nice formatting similar to LaTeX, while code should be written in code cells. There, the code can be run interactively and the output will be visualized in the notebook.

You can change the cell content with 'm' for markup and 'y' for code. Remember that you need to be in selection (or command) mode. 


```python
# Try running this code to see how the result is diplayed
1 + 1
```




    



# A standard machine learning example
## Loading libraries
Most of the functionality that we need is provided by additional libraries to the core python. At the beginning of the code, we need to load these packages.

Python is stricter than R when it comes to namespaces. When loading a function from a package, the package is usually included in the function call. For convenience, package names are therefore often abbreviated using import ... as ... . It is also possible to import only specific function from a library using from 'package' import 'function'.

An important package to remember is 'scikit-learn' the standard package for machine learning in python. You can find its documentation here [http://scikit-learn.org/stable/documentation.html].

## Object classes and loading data
Unlike R, Python is primarily a programming language, so its standard object classes behave a little different. The biggest difference is that many objects can be modified in-place, i.e. without reassignment common in R like x <- x[1:2]. This increases speed and memory efficiency, but be careful when running code multiple times or in a different order. Also be aware that objects are not copied when reassigned, but instead linked to the original content, which may change. If you'd like to copy a list, use a complete index [:].

When indexing lists and similar objects, always remember that python starts counting indices at 0. When slicing x[start:end], the end value is *not* included in the output.


```python
# Lists
x = [4, 5, 1, 2]
print(x)

print(x[1:3])
```

## Dictionaries
Dictionaries are similar to named lists in R, in that they save a value filed under a name (=key). When creating object classes, python makes use of different brackets.


```python
# Dictionary
d = {"a":2, "b":"cheese", "c":[1,2,3]}
print(d)
print(d["c"])
print(d["b"])
```

## Functions & Methods
Functions work as in R. You create new function by *defining* them. You see that much of structural programming is indicated by the structure of the code, i.e. a tab or four spaces.

Python is a an object-oriented programming language, so in addition to functions, it has *methods*. Methods are associated with objects. That means they are called for a specific object instead of passing the object as an explicit argument and have access to information saved within the class. 



```python
# Functions
def example_function(x, y = 2):
    y += 2 # This is short for add and reassign y = y + 2
    return(str(x) + str(y)) # str() transforms to strings and strings can be 'added' for convinience.

print(example_function("a"))
```

## Model tuning (with cross validation)


```python
# Crossvalidation in combination with grid search

# cross_val_score uses stratified sampling be default
# Crossvalidation und parameter selection via grid search

# Selection of parameters with (few and unrealistic!) example values:
# n_estimators : integer (default=10 --> The number of trees in the forest.
# max_features : int, float, string or None (default=”auto”) The number of features to consider when looking for the best split
# criterion : string (default=”gini”), or entropy
# max_depth : integer or None (default=None) The maximum depth of the tree.
# min_samples_split : int, float (default=2) --> The minimum number of samples required to split an internal node.
# min_samples_leaf : int, float (default=1) --> The minimum number of samples required to be at a leaf node.
param_grid = {'n_estimators': [10, 20, 30], 
              'max_features': ['log2', 'sqrt','auto'], 
              'criterion': ['entropy', 'gini'], # More detailed than caret
              'max_depth': [5, 10], 
              'min_samples_split': [4],
              'min_samples_leaf': [10]
             }

# Set up the grid object specifying the tuning options
grid = GridSearchCV(myModel, param_grid, cv = 3, scoring = 'roc_auc')
grid.fit(X_train, y_train)

print(grid.best_score_)
print(grid.best_params_)

# Set the clf to the best combination of parameters
myBestModel = grid.best_estimator_

# Fit the best algorithm to the data. 
myBestModel.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred_best = myBestModel.predict(X_test)
y_pred_best_prob = myBestModel.predict_proba(X_test)[:,1]
print('AUC of best model: ', metrics.roc_auc_score(y_test, y_pred_best_prob))
print("\n")
```

# Keras

# Loading keras
Keras is a wrapper for different software libraries that implement deep neural networks, most importantly Tensorflow and Theano. You can use any of these software libraries directly, but keras provides some higher-level functions that may reduce your flexibility, but make setting up a network much easier.

You can switch between the underlying libraries by adjusting the keras setup file as explained in the documentation [https://keras.io/backend/]. 

## Data preparation


```python
# Split data into a training and test set
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X.as_matrix(), y.as_matrix(), test_size = 0.4, random_state = 0)
print(type(X_train))
print(type(y_train))
      
```

## The sequential API / Setting up the model


```python
import keras
from keras.models import Sequential

from keras.layers import Dense, Activation, Dropout

from keras.regularizers import l2
from keras.optimizers import SGD, Adam
```

The official tutorial to the sequential model can be found here https://keras.io/getting-started/sequential-model-guide/


```python
# Create a new sequential model
model = Sequential()

# You can create new layers with the add() method
model.add(Dense(16, activation='relu', kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01), input_dim = 8))
#model.add(Dropout(0.2)) # This counteracts overfitting
model.add(Dense(16, kernel_regularizer=l2(0.01), activation='relu'))
#model.add(Dropout(0.2))
model.add(Dense(1, activation='sigmoid')) # Sigmoid, the logit function, gives probability outputs
```

## Training the model

Training the model (or fitting the model weights) is done in two steps. First, we specify an optimization procedure and a loss function. Second, we pass the data to the model and tell it for how long to train. We can also pass some validation data to get updates on how we do on unknown data during the training. This can help us to identify overfitting.


```python
model.fit(x = X_train, y = y_train, # Pass the training data as numpy arrays
          validation_data=[X_test, y_test], # Pass the validation data as a list
          epochs = 1000, # Pass the number of runs through the whole data
          batch_size=64) # Pass the number of observations that are used for each weight update. Useful for large data!
```
